{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17635368","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17635368"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:13:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:13:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17542"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17542","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17542"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.75,0.09,0.06,0.03,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10232"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74656"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10232","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10232"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17542"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60141"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"2778"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"6103"},{"type":"tags","id":"7234"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23930"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23933"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74656","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74656"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-week history of difficulty in extending his knee after a sports injury where he sustained a strong blow or impact to the anterior hip. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination reveals weakness in knee extension and diminished sensation over the anterior thigh.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following nerves is most likely affected in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Femoral nerve","Obturator nerve","Sciatic nerve","Superficial fibular nerve","Tibial nerve"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efemoral nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is responsible for innervating the anterior compartment of the thigh, which includes the quadriceps muscle group. This group is primarily involved in knee extension. The patient\u0027s symptoms of difficulty in extending the knee and diminished sensation over the anterior thigh suggest an issue with the femoral nerve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be excluded for the following reasons:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObturator nerve\u003C/strong\u003E: innervates the medial compartment of the thigh, responsible for adduction of the thigh\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESciatic nerve\u003C/strong\u003E: innervates the posterior compartment of the thigh and the entire lower leg and foot\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuperficial fibular nerve\u003C/strong\u003E: innervates the lateral compartment of the leg, responsible for foot eversion\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETibial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E: innervates the posterior compartment of the leg, responsible for plantarflexion of the foot\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe location of the trauma (anterior hip) and the specific pattern of weakness (knee extension) and sensory loss (anterior thigh) are classic for femoral nerve injury.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The femoral nerve is responsible for innervating the anterior compartment of the thigh.","The anterior compartment of the thigh primarily contains muscles involved in knee extension.","Femoral nerve injury should be suspected with weakness of knee extension and anterior thigh numbness following trauma."],"references":["Refai NA, Black AC, Tadi P. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Thigh Femoral Nerve. 2023 Aug 22. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32310525.","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Science","Merryman J, Varacallo M. Klumpke Palsy. 2023 Aug 4. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30285395"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60141"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17542"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60141","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60141"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-26T10:49:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-26T15:11:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10232"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74656"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09